# No Real Names in Source Code

This is a public open-source project. Real names, emails, employee IDs, and any other personally identifiable info of team members must **never** appear in code, comments, fixtures, tests, commit messages, or filenames committed to the repo.

Real participant data lives only in the runtime UI (entered by the user in the browser, persisted to `localStorage`) and in CSV/JSON files the user keeps locally. The codebase itself must stay generic.

## What to do

- For examples, options, comments, and tests use **placeholders**: `Alice Johnson`, `Bob Smith`, `Team A`, `alice@example.com`.
- For runtime defaults pull values from the user's own session (e.g. `/api/auth/me`, `localStorage`, user input) — never hardcode.
- If a feature seems to need a list of teammates baked in (dropdown, mapping, etc.), reach for a UI input or auto-detection instead.

## Examples

```js
// ❌ BAD — real teammate baked in
const DEVS = [
  { value: 'Vitaly_Lyutarevich', label: 'Vitaly Lyutarevich' },
  { value: 'Denis_Petrenko',     label: 'Denis Petrenko' },
];
const EMAIL_MAP = { 'vitaly.lyutarevich@gmail.com': 'Vitaly_Lyutarevich' };

// ✅ GOOD — derive from auth response at runtime
const me = await fetchJsonOrNull('/api/auth/me');
const filename = sanitize(me?.name ?? '');
```

```js
// ❌ BAD — real email in test fixture
const fixture = { email: 'denis.petrenko@realcompany.com' };

// ✅ GOOD — placeholder
const fixture = { email: 'alice@example.com' };
```

If real data is needed for a one-off local debug, keep the file untracked (gitignored) and never reference it from source.
